In conversation with @chandrarsrikanth on why and how @mamaearth.in came to life. 
The parental stress of providing the safest products to Agasthya was indeed the driving force behind Mamaearth.

From being called ‘Google Parents’ for our paranoia to reading the labels of hundreds of products and going the extra mile to learn about product formulations and ingredient regulations, it all came down to one thing -  solving that one problem we felt so strongly about.

Here’s a little snippet of our story covered by @cnnnews18 India and what propelled us to build Mamaearth.

Jab last year @sharktank.india se call aaya, main thoda hesitate kar rahi thi from entering the show. I had got to know that I was pregnant the second time and shooting was supposed to happen when I would be time 7 months pregnant. With massive weight gain, hormonal changes, swollen feet, last trimester is always tricky. Should I take on more responsibility I asked myself. 
But then, I thought ki yahi to mauka hai, to prove that women don’t have to slow down when they are pregnant. I decided to take it up.
My biggest joy was when a lot of mothers wrote back that they got inspired to get back to work. Bahut sari to-be-moms ne likha ki wo bhi life or career dono sath me leke chalengi. 
The only way we as a country can grow disproportionately and fairly is to have more women participating in the economy.
Thank you @entrepreneurind for bringing out my candidness in this interview. One of the rare ones where I am speaking my heart out. 

#womeninbusiness

The journey of building mamaearth has been an emotional one with a lot of moments which have tried to break my spirit. It’s something any entrepreneur especially females will go through on both personal and professional one. If there is one thing that I have learnt is for a 1000 naysayers and nonbelievers you just need a few believers who will back you, help you and cheer for you come what may. Just keep these believers close and ignore every other noise. The only people you need to take feedback from are your consumers, you don’t owe anyone else anything. Go build just like #shebuilds. latestPosts.caption:
From a 2-member team ➡️ 700+ employees
From a dingy basement ➡️ a 30,000 Sqft office 
From 6 products ➡️ 300+ products
From individually planting trees ➡️ 347311 trees. 
From a tiny popup ➡️ 50 stores across India!
From 1 brand to ➡️ 6 brands 

6 years ago @varunalagh and I started with a dream. A dream to create products that are honest, safe, and empower our consumers.💫

Since then, we have grown not only as individuals but as partners as well. In times of uncertainty, our values have guided us to make tough decisions with strength and comfort, knowing that we are moving in the right direction.

I’m so grateful to our consumers, our team, our suppliers, customer and all of there families for their support at every step of the way. Your love and contribution have helped us reach here and beyond.🙏♥️ 

Here’s to 6 wonderful years of Mamaearth ✨🥳

Swipe right the pictures to go through our journey from December 2016 to today. 

#MamaearthTurns6

latestPosts.caption:
Being on the cover of @business_today with these exceptional women @katrinakaif & madhuripuri is truly special, and I can’t be more grateful 🙏

Being a working women there are 4 things that I believe we all should do to support women and inclusivity in business. 

⚡Recognising Bias at Home
Giving our boys legos and our girls dolls will only reinforce gender stereotypes. Allow your kids to experience both, that's the first step towards raising them equally.

⚡Mentorship
Every woman entrepreneur must mentor at least three more women and encourage them to do the same. By doing this, we can help more women succeed in business.

⚡Sharing responsibilities in marriage
Kids learn from what they see. By setting this example in our own households, we invest in our future generation so that they don't see this bias.

⚡Equal hiring opportunities 
When hiring for any position, pull out an equal number of CVs for both the genders to ensure an inclusive workplace. We make sure that we implement this approach at @Honasa Consumer Pvt Ltd, and I am proud to say that 51% of our business is run by women.

It feels great to be recognised for some small initiatives that I with @varunalagh take to play our part in the society, Thank you @Business Today 🙏

Behind every successful woman, there is a supportive and progressive man. Thank you @Varun Alagh for being my biggest pillar of support & strength and for inspiring me to take more challenges and do my best each time.
You are the wind beneath my wings♥️

#womanentrepreneur #featured #grateful

latestPosts.caption:
Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer, had a very shiny nose… 🎶

Every year we decorate our christmas tree and sing jingles together as a family. This year while we were following this tradition, my younger son asked me:

“Who’s Rudolph? Is he the one who pulls Santa’s sleigh?”

This question led to a surprising discovery. 

Santa’s reindeer aren’t male but they’re actually female! 🦌❄️

Male reindeer shed their antlers by mid-December, but female reindeer keep theirs through Christmas. That means the sleigh delivering joy across the world is powered by a team of strong, resilient women!

This realization got me thinking about how deeply ingrained gender biases can be. Even though Santa’s reindeer are female, they’ve been assumed to be male and given traditionally male names like Rudolph, Dasher, Prancer, and Cupid.

But here’s the heart of the story which is also a beautiful reminder of the strength, leadership, and determination women bring to every part of life whether it’s at home, at work, or even in guiding Santa’s sleigh through the night sky.

This isn’t about glorifying overwork but about celebrating resilience and breaking barriers.

So here’s to all the incredible women out there leading, lifting, and shaping the future. 

You are the real magic of this season.

#christmas #santaclaus #rudolph
